"Kutz S.J., Jenkins E.J., Veitch A.M., Ducrocq J., Polley L., Elkin B., Lair S.","The Arctic as a model for anticipating, preventing, and mitigating climate change impacts on host-parasite interactions",2009,"Veterinary Parasitology","163","3",,"217","228",,,10.1016/j.vetpar.2009.06.008,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-67649458008&partnerID=40&md5=1286e863c6e56850cd1a18119bb697f5","Department of Ecosystem and Public Health, Faculty of Veterinary Medicine, University of Calgary, 3330 Hospital Dr. NW, Calgary, AB T2N 4N1, Canada","Kutz, S.J., Department of Ecosystem and Public Health, Faculty of Veterinary Medicine, University of Calgary, 3330 Hospital Dr. NW, Calgary, AB T2N 4N1, Canada; Jenkins, E.J., Department of Ecosystem and Public Health, Faculty of Veterinary Medicine, University of Calgary, 3330 Hospital Dr. NW, Calgary, AB T2N 4N1, Canada; Veitch, A.M., Department of Ecosystem and Public Health, Faculty of Veterinary Medicine, University of Calgary, 3330 Hospital Dr. NW, Calgary, AB T2N 4N1, Canada; Ducrocq, J., Department of Ecosystem and Public Health, Faculty of Veterinary Medicine, University of Calgary, 3330 Hospital Dr. NW, Calgary, AB T2N 4N1, Canada; Polley, L., Department of Ecosystem and Public Health, Faculty of Veterinary Medicine, University of Calgary, 3330 Hospital Dr. NW, Calgary, AB T2N 4N1, Canada; Elkin, B., Department of Ecosystem and Public Health, Faculty of Veterinary Medicine, University of Calgary, 3330 Hospital Dr. NW, Calgary, AB T2N 4N1, Canada; Lair, S., Department of Ecosystem and Public Health, Faculty of Veterinary Medicine, University of Calgary, 3330 Hospital Dr. NW, Calgary, AB T2N 4N1, Canada","Climate change is influencing the structure and function of natural ecosystems around the world, including host-parasite interactions and disease emergence. Understanding the influence of climate change on infectious disease at temperate and tropical latitudes can be challenging because of numerous complicating biological, social, and political factors. Arctic and Subarctic regions may be particularly good models for unraveling the impacts of climate change on parasite ecology because they are relatively simple systems with low biological diversity and few other complicating anthropogenic factors. We examine some changing dynamics of host-parasite interactions at high latitudes and use these to illustrate a framework for approaching understanding, preventing, and mitigating climate change impacts on infectious disease, including zoonoses, in wildlife. © 2009.","Arctic; Climate change; Global warming; Parasites; Subarctic; Wildlife","Arctic; article; climate change; endemic disease; environmental impact; environmental monitoring; environmental temperature; geographic distribution; greenhouse effect; host parasite interaction; human; infection prevention; latitude; nonhuman; parasite control; parasite transmission; parasitosis; risk factor; zoonosis; Animals; Animals, Wild; Arctic Regions; Ecosystem; Greenhouse Effect; Host-Parasite Interactions; Parasitic Diseases, Animal; Zoonoses",,,,,,"Albon, S.D., Stien, A., Irvine, R.J., Langvatn, R., Ropstad, E., Halvorsen, O., The role of parasites in the dynamics of a reindeer population (2002) Proc. Roy. Soc. Lond. B, 269, pp. 1625-1632; Bernstein, L., Climate Change 2007: Synthesis Report (2009) Intergovernmental Panel on Climate Change. Intergovernmental Panel on Climate Change: Fourth Assessment Report, pp. 1-52. , Allali, A, Bojariu, R, Diaz, S, Elgizouli, I, Griggs, D, Hawkins, D, Hohmeyer, O, Jallow, B.P, Kajfez-Bogataj, L, Leary, N, Lee, H, Wratt, D, Eds; Bradley, M., Wilmshurst, J., The fall and rise of bison populations in Wood Buffalo National Park: 1971 to 2003 (2005) Can. J. Zool., 83, pp. 1195-1205; Brunetti, O.A., Redescription of Parelaphostrongylus (Boev and Schuls, 1950) in California deer, with studies on its life history and pathology (1969) Calif. Fish Game, 55, pp. 307-316; Deem, S.L., Karesh, W.B., Weisman, W., 